\details{
This helper is intended for inequality-aware tree fitting where the response
contains a socioeconomic ranking variable and a health outcome. Unlike
\code{\link[partykit:ctree]{partykit::ctree()}}, it does not use conditional-inference tests for
first-stage variable selection.

At each non-terminal node \code{t}, \code{ci_tree()} searches across all
candidate variables and all admissible split points, then selects the pair
with the largest concentration-index gain:
\deqn{(j^*, s^*) =
\arg\max_{j \in \mathcal{J}_t,\ s \in \mathcal{S}_{jt}}
G_m(t, j, s).}
The gain \code{G_m} is computed by \code{\link[=weighted_ci_gain]{weighted_ci_gain()}} from the selected
concentration-index impurity \code{m}, one of \code{"CI"}, \code{"CIg"}, \code{"CIc"}, or
\code{"L"}.

The fitted object uses \code{\link[partykit:party]{partykit::party()}} for storage, traversal,
prediction, and plotting, but the tree-growing rule is the package's greedy
concentration-index rule rather than the conditional-inference test-based
rule used by \code{\link[partykit:ctree]{partykit::ctree()}}.

Stopping rules operate in three places. First, a node is searched only when
it satisfies \code{minsplit} and has not reached \code{maxdepth}. Second, candidate
splits are admissible only when both child nodes satisfy \code{minbucket} and
\code{minprob}. Third, after all admissible splits are scored, the best split is
accepted only when its gain is finite and greater than \code{min_gain}.
}
